    <h1>Common Fundamental Analysis & Valuation Methods</h1>
    
    <h2>3.1 üìä Earnings Per Share (EPS)</h2>
    
    <h3>1. Definition and Formula</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/valuation/image.png" alt="EPS Formula" style="max-width: 672px;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>Simple understanding: EPS represents the profit earned per share for shareholders.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>2. Why is it Important?</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>EPS is the foundation for many valuation methods (such as <strong>P/E ratio</strong>).</li>
        <li>High EPS indicates strong profitability.</li>
        <li>Consistently growing EPS shows the company's profits are steadily expanding.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3. Usage</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Investors often compare EPS with stock price to judge if a stock is "expensive" or "cheap".</li>
        <li>Analyzing EPS trends is more important than a single year (e.g., has EPS grown year-over-year over the past 5 years?).</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>4. Industry Differences</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Consumer Staples</strong>: EPS is stable but grows slowly.</li>
        <li><strong>Technology Industry</strong>: EPS may fluctuate significantly, but has higher growth potential.</li>
        <li><strong>Financial Industry</strong>: EPS is affected by interest rates and economic cycles.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>3.2 üìà Earnings Growth Rate</h2>
    
    <h3>1. Definition and Formula</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/valuation/image%201.png" alt="Earnings Growth Rate Formula" style="max-width: 768px;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>It represents the growth rate of the company's profits.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>2. Why is it Important?</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Determines the company's future value. Even if current profits are modest, high growth rate can make it a good investment.</li>
        <li><strong>PEG Ratio</strong> combines P/E with growth rate to judge if valuation is reasonable.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3. Usage</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Growth companies (like Nvidia, Meta) typically attract investors with high growth rates.</li>
        <li>Mature companies (like Coca-Cola) have lower growth rates but are more stable.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>4. Industry Differences</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Tech Stocks</strong>: Growth rate may be >20%, but volatile.</li>
        <li><strong>Consumer Staples</strong>: Growth rate typically <10%, but resilient.</li>
        <li><strong>Financial Industry</strong>: Growth rate is closely related to economic cycles and interest rate environment.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>üìù Summary</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>EPS</strong> = profit per share ‚Üí reflects current profitability.</li>
        <li><strong>Earnings Growth Rate</strong> = profit growth speed ‚Üí reflects future growth potential.</li>
        <li>When investing, look at both <strong>EPS level</strong> and <strong>growth rate trends</strong>.</li>
        <li>üëâ Example: Nvidia has high EPS + fast growth ‚Üí high valuation is reasonable.</li>
        <li>Coca-Cola has stable EPS + low growth ‚Üí suitable for defensive investment.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>3.3a üìä Price-to-Earnings Ratio (P/E)</h2>
    
    <h3>1. Definition and Formula</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/valuation/image%202.png" alt="P/E Formula" style="max-width: 528px;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>Represents how much investors are willing to pay per share for each $1 of current earnings.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>2. Why is it Important?</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>P/E is the most common valuation metric.</li>
        <li>Can quickly judge if a company is "cheap" or "expensive".</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3. Usage</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Most suitable for mature industries and companies with stable profits.</li>
        <li>If a company is losing money or profits fluctuate significantly, P/E is less accurate.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>4. Industry Differences</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Consumer Staples</strong>: P/E typically 15‚Äì25x.</li>
        <li><strong>Tech Growth Stocks</strong>: P/E may be 25‚Äì40x or even higher.</li>
        <li><strong>Banking/Finance</strong>: P/E is relatively low, typically 10‚Äì15x.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>Advantages: Simple and intuitive, most common.</p>
    <p>Disadvantages: P/E can be distorted when profits fluctuate significantly. Not suitable for companies losing money.</p>
    
    <h2>3.3b üìä Price-to-Book Ratio (P/B)</h2>
    
    <h3>1. Definition and Formula</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/valuation/image%203.png" alt="P/B Formula" style="max-width: 528px;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>Represents the multiple of stock price relative to the company's book value.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>2. Why is it Important?</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Reflects the market's recognition of the company's asset value.</li>
        <li>If P/B < 1, it means the stock price may be below the company's book value (possibly undervalued, or the market thinks asset quality is poor).</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3. Usage</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Especially suitable for <strong>banks, insurance, real estate</strong> - asset-driven companies.</li>
        <li>For light-asset tech companies, P/B has limited reference value.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>4. Industry Differences</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Banking</strong>: P/B typically 1‚Äì2x, high ROE banks command a premium.</li>
        <li><strong>Manufacturing/Cyclical Stocks</strong>: P/B typically 1‚Äì3x.</li>
        <li><strong>Tech/Platform Companies</strong>: P/B is relatively high, not suitable as sole valuation basis.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>3.4 üìä PEG Ratio (Price/Earnings to Growth)</h2>
    
    <h3>1. Definition and Formula</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Formula</strong>Ôºö</li>
    </ul>
    <figure>
        <img src="/images/unit1/valuation/image%204.png" alt="PEG Formula" style="max-width: 432px;">
    </figure>
    <ul>
        <li>Combines valuation with the company's earnings growth rate.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>2. Why is it Important?</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Looking at P/E alone, high-growth companies may seem "expensive"; PEG can measure if growth is worth the premium.</li>
        <li>Generally, PEG ‚âà 1 is considered reasonable valuation.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>3. Usage</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Especially suitable for <strong>high-growth companies</strong> (like Nvidia, Meta, Google).</li>
        <li>Used to compare growth and valuation matching within the same industry.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>4. Industry Differences</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Technology Industry</strong>: PEG often > 1, but still reasonable if growth rate is very high.</li>
        <li><strong>Consumer Staples</strong>: Low growth, PEG often > 2, indicating expensive valuation but stable.</li>
        <li><strong>Financial Industry</strong>: Growth related to economic cycles, PEG should be interpreted with macro environment.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>3.5 Common Investor Misconceptions</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>‚ùå Misconception 1: High P/E = must be expensive.
            <ul>
                <li>‚Üí Correct: High-growth companies reasonably enjoy high P/E.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>‚ùå Misconception 2: DCF calculation gives accurate value.
            <ul>
                <li>‚Üí Correct: DCF is very sensitive to growth rate and discount rate, it's a "range judgment", not a single answer.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>‚ùå Misconception 3: All industries can use the same valuation method.
            <ul>
                <li>‚Üí Correct: Banks look at P/B, tech companies look at P/E + PEG, startups focus more on DCF assumptions.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>
